    {
      "$type": "Models.Core.Folder, Models",
      "ShowInDocs": false,
      "Name": "Wheat",
      "ResourceName": null,
      "Children": [
        {
          "$type": "Models.Memo, Models",
          "Text": "experimental data from DOI: 10.1111/jac.12486\n\nOutdoor experiments using canopies of wheat (Triticum aestivum L.), barley\n(Hordeum vulgare L.), oilseed rape (Brassica napus L.) and field pea (Pisum sativum L.)\nwere subjected to a 14-day-\nwaterlogging\nat early (vegetative) or late (reproductive)\nstages and a non-waterlogged\ntreatment (as control). Leaf area index (LAI), radiation\ninterception, radiation use efficiency (RUE) and aerial dry matter were monitored\nalong the life-cycle;\nquantifying yield and its components at maturity. Wheat was\nable to withstand waterlogging, with similar yields than controls. Barley showed no\ndifferences in yield at early stage, but late-waterlogging\nresulted in 64%–66%\nlower\nyield owing to fewer spikes/m2 and poor recovery of radiation interception and RUE\n",
          "Name": "Memo",
          "ResourceName": null,
          "Children": [],
          "Enabled": true,
          "ReadOnly": false
        },
        {
          "$type": "Models.Core.Simulation, Models",
